bt||nt|So, contrary to popular opinion, overtricks do matter at IMPs. Every Victory Point counted at this stage of the event. Canada was sitting in 3rd place with 2 matches to go. We were 13 VPs ahead of 5th place Poland. 13 VPs is a sizable gap at this late stage, but we could not afford to be comfortable - especially as we were about to play Poland!

Poland versus Canada turned out to be another low-scoring match. Poland won 24-19 in IMPs, but only 16-14 in Victory Points. The other matches also went well for Canada and we were all but mathematically assured of a qualifying spot going into the last match. Wow!

Nick rested Joey and I during the last match (against Egypt) and both partnerships had some anxious moments during this match. We got trounced - 24-6 in VPs, but we knew that we only needed 5 VPs to be assured of qualifying.  When the smoke cleared, Canada was sitting in 4th place with 140.7 VPs. Italy had won the round robin easily with the awesome score of 179 VPs. Norway finished second with 144.3 VPs and Poland finished in third, just ahead of us with 141.5 VPs. Indonesia was the highest non-qualifier with 135 VPs.

For the members of Team Canada, getting to the final four was something that none of us had really expected. It was a serious thrill to have come this far and the excitement was not about to let up. Italy, by virtue of winning the round robin, was entitled to chose their semi-final opponents from among the other 3 qualifiers. Nobody was surprised, of course, when they selected Canada. Italy would enjoy a 6 IMP carryover into our 48-board semi-final.

We know we are big favorites to lose this match, but stranger things have happened...

